      "content": "A key argument is that government regulation of the internet infringes upon the absolute freedom of expression enshrined in the First Amendment, as embodied by the concept of \"no prior restraint\" in landmark Supreme Court cases like New York Times v. Sullivan (1964) and Ginsberg v. New York (1968). This perspective posits that government censorship is inherently unconstitutional and that all regulation is a form of prior restraint. Additionally, the concept of the \"free market\" can be used to argue that the internet is a natural extension of private enterprise, and thus, regulation is a form of government overreach.",
